{"title_page": "98th Illinois Infantry Regiment", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 98th Regiment Illinois Volunteer Infantry\n| image=Flag of Illinois.svg\n| image_size = 100\n|caption=Illinois flag\n|dates= September 3, 1862, to July 29, 1865\n|country= [[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[Mounted infantry]]\n|equipment= [[Spencer repeating rifle]]\n| battles = [[American Civil War]]\n* [[Battle of Hoover's Gap]]\n* [[Battle of Chickamauga]]\n* [[Battle of Resaca]]\n* [[Siege of Atlanta]]\n}}\nThe '''98th Regiment Illinois Volunteer Infantry''', later the '''98th Regiment Illinois Mounted Infantry''', was an [[infantry]] [[regiment]] that served in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Service==\nThe 98th Illinois Infantry was organized at [[Centralia, Illinois]] and mustered into Federal service on September 3, 1862.\n\nThe regiment was converted to mounted infantry on March 8, 1863. An element of \"Wilder's [[Lightning Brigade (US Army of the Cumberland 1863)|Lightning Brigade]]\", a unit that pioneered the use of [[mounted infantry]].\n\nThe regiment was mustered out on June 27, 1865, and discharged at [[Springfield, Illinois]], on July 7, 1865.\n\n==Total strength and casualties==\nThe regiment suffered 30 enlisted men who were killed in action or who died of their wounds and 5 officers and 136 enlisted men who died of disease, for a total of 171 fatalities.<ref>http://www.civilwararchive.com/Unreghst/unilinf8.htm#98th The Civil War Archive website after Dyer, Frederick Henry. '''A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion'''. 3 vols. New York: Thomas Yoseloff, 1959.</ref>\n\n==Commanders==\n*Colonel John J. Funkhouser - Discharged due to wounds July 5, 1864.<ref>http://www.rootsweb.com/~ilcivilw/f&s/098-fs.htm Illinois in the Cvil war website after Illinois Adjutant General's muster rolls</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Illinois Civil War Units]]\n*[[Illinois in the American Civil War]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.civilwararchive.com/unionil.htm The Civil War Archive]\n\n[[Category:Illinois Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:1862 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1862]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n\n\n{{AmericanCivilWar-unit-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 98th Regiment Illinois Volunteer Infantry\n| image=Flag of Illinois.svg\n| image_size = 100\n|caption=Illinois flag\n|dates= September 3, 1862, to July 29, 1865\n|country= [[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[Mounted infantry]]\n|equipment= [[Spencer repeating rifle]]\n| battles = [[American Civil War]]\n* [[Battle of Hoover's Gap]]* [[Battle of Chickamauga]]* [[Battle of Resaca]]<BR>[[Siege of Atlanta]]\n}}\nThe '''98th Regiment Illinois Volunteer Infantry''', later the '''98th Regiment Illinois Mounted Infantry''', was an [[infantry]] [[regiment]] that served in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Service==\nThe 98th Illinois Infantry was organized at [[Centralia, Illinois]] and mustered into Federal service on September 3, 1862.\n\nThe regiment was converted to mounted infantry on March 8, 1863. An element of \"Wilder's [[Lightning Brigade (US Army of the Cumberland 1863)|Lightning Brigade]]\", a unit that pioneered the use of [[mounted infantry]].\n\nThe regiment was mustered out on June 27, 1865, and discharged at [[Springfield, Illinois]], on July 7, 1865.\n\n==Total strength and casualties==\nThe regiment suffered 30 enlisted men who were killed in action or who died of their wounds and 5 officers and 136 enlisted men who died of disease, for a total of 171 fatalities.<ref>http://www.civilwararchive.com/Unreghst/unilinf8.htm#98th The Civil War Archive website after Dyer, Frederick Henry. '''A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion'''. 3 vols. New York: Thomas Yoseloff, 1959.</ref>\n\n==Commanders==\n*Colonel John J. Funkhouser - Discharged due to wounds July 5, 1864.<ref>http://www.rootsweb.com/~ilcivilw/f&s/098-fs.htm Illinois in the Cvil war website after Illinois Adjutant General's muster rolls</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Illinois Civil War Units]]\n*[[Illinois in the American Civil War]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.civilwararchive.com/unionil.htm The Civil War Archive]\n\n[[Category:Illinois Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:1862 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1862]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n\n\n{{AmericanCivilWar-unit-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/98th_Illinois_Infantry_Regiment"}
{"title_page": "Chad Fischer", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{ infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name  = Chad Fischer\n| image = \n| caption = \n| background = solo_singer\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = \n| Nationality = \n| birth_place = \n| instrument = Vocals, guitar, bass, drums, keyboard\n| genre = [[Alternative rock]], [[indie rock]]\n| occupation = Musician, producer, songwriter\n| years_active = 1991\u2013present\n| label = Fish of Death, [[Almo Sounds]], Lookout Sound, [[Hollywood Records]]\n| associated_acts = [[School of Fish]], A Don Piper Situation, [[Lazlo Bane]], [[Lazlo Bane#The (Silent) Rage|The (Silent) Rage]], [[Colin Hay]], [[The Blanks]], [[Cary Brothers]], [[Larry Goldings]], [[Alexi Murdoch]], [[Joshua Radin]], [[Lisa Loeb]], [[Teddy Geiger]], [[The Good Luck Joes]]\n| website = {{URL|www.chadfischermusic.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Chad Fischer''' is an American singer-songwriter, multi-instrumentalist, composer and producer from [[Santa Monica]], California, also known as a frontman of the band [[Lazlo Bane]].\n\n==Early years==\n{{See also|School of Fish}}\nChad Fischer's early work was being a drummer for the band [[School of Fish]] founded by his college friend [[Josh Clayton-Felt]]. Fischer replaced the original drummer M.P. in 1991, however he did not play on the band's [[Human Cannonball (album)|second album]] due to fallout with a producer and was replaced by [[Josh Freese]].<ref name=pauseandplay>{{cite web|url=http://www.pauseandplay.com/lazlo-bane-wants-to-be-your-superman/|title=Lazlo Bane wants to be your 'Superman'|work=Pauseandplay.com|accessdate=20 October 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021052156/http://www.pauseandplay.com/lazlo-bane-wants-to-be-your-superman/|archive-date=October 21, 2013}}</ref> Nevertheless, Fischer still stayed with the band to perform live.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.2ndfirstlook.com/2010/12/school-of-fish.html|title=School of Fish: The Best Lesson Learned|date= December 27, 2010|publisher=2ndfirstlook.com|accessdate=20 February 2019}}</ref> The only official commercial School of Fish release that included his drumming was the single \"Take Me Anywhere\", which included two live tracks as [[b-side]]s.<ref>\"Take Me Anywhere\" CD single liner notes</ref>\n\nAfter School of Fish disbanded in 1994 Chad Fischer went on to build his own recording studio and started to write new material.<ref name=pauseandplay/> He signed to [[Almo Sounds]] label and formed the band Lazlo Bane, whose debut album, ''[[11 Transistor]]'' was released in January 1997.<ref name=almo>{{cite web|url=http://www.onamrecords.com/Almo_Sounds.html|title= Almo Sounds History|publisher=onamrecords.com|accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring the early years Chad Fischer met [[Colin Hay]] with whom he became a close friend. Fisher played drums on Hay's 1994 album ''[[Topanga (album)|Topanga]]'', while Hay contributed guitar and vocals to Lazlo Bane's [[cover version|cover]] of \"[[Overkill (Men at Work song)|Overkill]]\" from their debut album. Since then Chad Fischer took part in recording of every Hay's subsequent studio album up to ''Next Year People'' in 2015, with Fischer's role varying from [[session musician]] and songwriter to [[mixing engineer]] and co-producer.\n\nFischer was briefly a member of Don Piper's band A Don Piper Situation playing drums, producing and engineering the track \"Ray Falls Down\" on the self-titled 1997 EP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adonpipersituation.net/music|title=A Don Piper Situation music|publisher=adonpipersituation.net|accessdate=4 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Work with Lazlo Bane==\n{{See also|Lazlo Bane}}\nAfter Almo Sounds was bought by [[Universal Music Publishing Group|Universal Music Group]]<ref name=almo/> Lazlo Bane continued their career as an [[Independent music|independent band]].<ref name=pauseandplay/> Chad Fischer continued to produce Lazlo Bane albums with them being released through self-established label Lookout Sound.\n\nThe band's second album ''[[All the Time in the World (Lazlo Bane album)|All the Time in the World]]'' was released in 2002. It included the song \"[[Superman (Lazlo Bane song)|Superman]]\", which became the Lazlo Bane's most recognizable song as it became a theme song for the popular American TV series ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]''.<ref name=pauseandplay/> Chad Fischer along with Lazlo Bane members Tim Bright and Chris Link as songwriters of \"Superman\" and Scrubs' composer Jan Stevens won [[Broadcast Music, Inc.|BMI]] TV Music Award of 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/2003_bmi_film_tv_awards_song_list|title=2003 BMI Film/TV Awards: Song List|publisher=bmi.com|date=May 14, 2003|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> and 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmi.com/press/entry/534596|title=2004 BMI Film/TV Awards: Song List|publisher=bmi.com|date=May 12, 2004|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nOver the next decade Lazlo Bane released two more studio albums and one [[Extended Play|EP]], all of them independently. Another album by the band, ''[[Big Spill (The Rage album)|Big Spill]]'', was released in 2013 and was credited to [[Lazlo Bane#The (Silent) Rage|The Rage]], Lazlo Bane's [[alter ego]] project.\n\n==Solo career==\nIn October 2019 Chad Fischer released his first non film and TV series related album of music titled ''National Parks'' which was dedicated to the American [[national parks]] and [[National monument (United States)|monuments]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chadfischermusic.com/|title=About National Parks|publisher=chadfischermusic.com|accessdate=2019-10-21}}</ref>\n\n==Films and TV series scoring==\n\n===Films===\n{{See also|Category:Films scored by Chad Fischer}}\nIn the beginning of 2000s Chad Fischer started providing music and songs for various films and TV shows.\n\nHis first full-length film for which he provided the scores was ''[[Garden State (film)|Garden State]]'', released in 2004. Both the film and [[Garden State soundtrack|its soundtrack]] proved to be critically and commercially acclaimed. ''Garden State'' also featured Fischer's original song called \"Motorcycle Ride with Sam\". It hasn't been officially released, but it is available to listen in the DVD menu of the film and on Chad Fischer's Myspace page.<ref name=Myspace>[http://www.myspace.com/chadfischermusic Chad Fischer], on Myspace</ref>\n\n2005 film ''[[Little Manhattan]]'' featured new songs, both by Chad Fischer and Lazlo Bane, that were written especially for the film. It also featured a cover of [[The Beatles]]' song \"[[In My Life]]\" produced by Fischer and performed by [[Matt Scannell]]. The soundtrack for the album remains unreleased with only one Fischer's song, \"Map of My Heart\", available to listen on his [[Myspace]] page.<ref name=Myspace/> However, promotional compilation of Chad Fischer's music from ''Garden State'' and ''Little Manhattan'' also featuring his production work was released circa 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Chad-Fischer-The-Film-Music-Of-Chad-Fischer-Garden-StateLittle-Manhattan/release/10780123|title=The Film Music of Chad Fischer|publisher=discogs|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2008 film ''[[The Rocker (film)|The Rocker]]'' Chad Fischer wrote the score<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmmusicmag.com/?p=1151|title=\"The Rocker\" Assigned to Chad Fischer|publisher=filmmusicmag.com|author=Mikael Carlsson|date=May 13, 2008|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref> and a number of original songs which were performed by fictional bands A.D.D. and Vesuvius. The actual music was mostly performed by Chad Fischer himself with the vocals provided by [[Teddy Geiger]] (for A.D.D.) and Keith England (for Vesuvius). A [[The Rocker: Music from the Motion Picture|soundtrack album]] that featured all the original material was also released in 2008.\n\nOn the 2009 film ''[[Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs]]'' Chad sing the another version of [[Gilbert O'Sullivan]]'s [[Alone Again (Naturally)]].\n\nOther films for which Fischer wrote the score are ''[[10 Years (2011 film)|10 Years]]'', ''[[Loosies]]'', ''[[The Babysitters]]'', ''[[Black Cloud (film)|Black Cloud]]'' and ''[[Chasing Mavericks]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2012/08/31/chad-fischer-scoring-chasing-mavericks/|title=Chad Fischer Scoring \u2018Chasing Mavericks\u2019|publisher=filmmusicreporter.com|date=August 31, 2012|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Chad Fischer returned to film scores with ''[[Eat, Brains, Love]]'' directed by [[Rodman Flender]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://filmmusicreporter.com/2018/08/14/chad-fischer-to-score-rodman-slenders-eat-brains-love/|title=Chad Fischer to Score Rodman Flender\u2019s \u2018Eat, Brains, Love\u2019|publisher=filmmusicreporter.com|date=August 14, 2018|accessdate=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nAside from film scores Chad Fischer wrote and performed a number of songs for the films he worked on, however none of them were released on any soundtrack albums or elsewhere.<ref name=IMDB>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0279412/?ref_=fn_al_nm_1|title= Chad Fischer on IMDB|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n===TV series===\nChad Fischer's early work on TV scores include shows ''[[My Guide to Becoming a Rock Star]]'' and ''[[The Class (TV series)|The Class]]''.\n\nIn 2007 Chad Fischer and Lazlo Bane guitarist Tim Bright started scoring American medical drama series ''[[Private Practice (TV series)|Private Practice]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.serenadaconceicao.com/blog/2015/2/19/rip-private-practice|title= RIP Private Practice |publisher=serenadaconceicao.com|date=December 10, 2012|accessdate=6 April 2016}}</ref> During its run Fischer and Bright won [[BMI Awards|BMI TV Music Award]] four times: in 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bmi.com/press/entry/536627|title=2008 BMI Film/TV Awards - Winners List|publisher=bmi.com|accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/private-practice/season-4/details|title= Private Practice : Season 4 |publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=6 April 2016}}</ref> 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmi.com/press/entry/538643|title= 2009 BMI Film & Television Music Awards Winners |publisher=bmi.com|accessdate=6 April 2016}}</ref> 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bmi.com/news/entry/2010_bmi_film_tv_award_winners|title=2010 BMI Film/TV Award Winners|publisher=bmi.com|accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref> and 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bmi.com/news/entry/rolfe_kent_receives_richard_kirk_award_at_bmi_film_tv_awards|title=Rolfe Kent Receives Richard Kirk Award at BMI Film & TV Awards|publisher=bmi.com|accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref> The show concluded after six seasons in 2013.\n\nAfter ''Private Practice'' Chad Fischer started providing music for another [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s show, ''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2011/09/16/chad-fischer-to-score-abcs-scandal/|title=Chad Fischer To Score ABC's \u2018Scandal\u2019|publisher=filmmusicreporter.com|date=September 16, 2011|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2012/12/13/scandal-music-alexandra-patsavas|title= Best of 2012 (Behind the Scenes): Music Supervisor Alexandra Patsavas scores with 'Scandal'|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=December 13, 2012|accessdate=6 April 2016}}</ref> For his work he won the BMI TV Music Award six times from 2013 to 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bmi.com/news/entry/cliff_martinez_and_top_composers_honored_at_the_2013_bmi_film_tv_awards|title=Cliff Martinez and Top Composers Honored at the 2013 BMI Film & TV Awards|publisher=bmi.com|accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2014/05/15/mychael-danna-honored-at-bmi-filmtv-awards/|title= Mychael Danna Honored at BMI Film & TV Awards|publisher=filmmusicreporter.com|date=May 15, 2014|accessdate=6 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/mychael_danna_and_top_composers_honored_at_2014_bmi_film_tv_awards|title= Mychael Danna and Top Composers Honored at 2014 BMI Film/TV Awards|publisher=bmi.com|date=May 15, 2014|accessdate=6 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bmi.com/news/entry/2015_bmi_film_tv_awards|title=Oscar-Winning Composer Alexandre Desplat Honored as BMI Icon at 2015 Film/TV Awards|publisher=bmi.com|accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bmi.com/photos/entry/574481|title=Composer James Newton Howard Honored as BMI Icon at 2016 Film/TV Awards|publisher=bmi.com|accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bmi.com/news/entry/film-tv-2017|title=Alan Silvestri Receives BMI Icon Award at 2017 BMI Film, TV and Visual Media Awards|publisher=bmi.com|accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bmi.com/news/entry/2018-bmi-film-tv-awards|title=John Williams Honored With Special Award at 34th Annual BMI Film, TV & Visual Media Awards|publisher=bmi.com|accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2018 the show's score album was released, consisting entirely of Chad Fischer's music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2018/01/18/score-album-for-abcs-scandal-to-be-released/|title=Score Album for ABC's \u2018Scandal\u2019 to Be Released|publisher=filmmusicreporter.com|date=January 18, 2018|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://crank11.news/2018/01/28/scandal-original-television-series-soundtrack/|title=Out on Spotify: \u2018Scandal (Original Television Series Soundtrack)\u2019 by Chad Fischer|publisher=crank11.news|author=Media Gazelle|date=January 28, 2018|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soundtrackdreams.com/2018/03/soundtrack-review-scandal-chad-fischer-2018/|title=Soundtrack review: Scandal (Chad Fischer \u2013 2018)|publisher=soundtrackdreams.com|author=Mihnea Manduteanu|date=March 26, 2018|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref> ''Scandal'' itself has also ended in 2018.\n\nIn 2016 Fischer started scoring yet another ABC's TV series ''[[The Catch (TV series)|The Catch]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2016/03/17/chad-fischer-scoring-abcs-the-catch/|title=Chad Fischer Scoring ABC's \u2018The Catch\u2019|publisher=filmmusicreporter.com|date=March 17, 2016|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref> The show ended in 2017.\n\nAfter ABC shows Chad Fischer scored the first season of the [[YouTube Premium]] original anthology 2019 series ''[[Weird City (TV series)|Weird City]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://filmmusicreporter.com/2019/01/28/youtube-premiums-weird-city-to-feature-original-score-by-chad-fischer/|title=YouTube Premium\u2019s \u2018Weird City\u2019 to Feature Original Score by Chad Fischer|publisher=filmmusicreporter.com|date=January 28, 2019|accessdate=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Record producer==\nChad Fischer started production work from the first Lazlo Bane album ''11 Transistor'' and produced every subsequent album of the band.\n\nAfter the death of Fischer's longtime friend and School of Fish bandmate Josh Clayton-Felt, he co-executive produced the release of ''[[Center of Six]]'', the second Clayton-Felt's posthumous album. It included several tribute songs produced by Chad Fischer and recorded by Josh's friends.\n\nFischer's production career progressed as he produced the first recordings and helped develop the sound of [[Cary Brothers]], [[Alexi Murdoch]] and [[Joshua Radin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waycoolmusic.net/musician/josh_radin/josh_radin.html|title=Josh Radin|publisher=waycoolmusic.net|accessdate=6 April 2016}}</ref> All of them later became successful musical acts.\n\nThe highly acclaimed ''[[Garden State (soundtrack)|Garden State soundtrack]]'', released in 2004, subsequently winning a [[Grammy Award]] in 2005<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/zach-braff|publisher=Grammy|title=Nominations and wins|accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> and receiving [[RIAA certification|platinum]] certification,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Paoletta|first=Michael|title=One Man, One Soundtrack|journal=Billboard|date=2007-09-22|page=32|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hQ4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA32&lpg=PA32|accessdate=22 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite certification|region=United States|title=Garden State}}</ref> featured two songs produced by Chad Fischer: \"Blue Eyes\" performed by Cary Brothers and \"Winding Road\" performed by actress [[Bonnie Somerville]].\n\nOther musicians and bands Fischer did production for feature [[Everlast (musician)|Everlast]], [[Lisa Loeb]], Colin Hay and [[The Good Luck Joes]] among others.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album details\n|-\n|2019\n|''National Parks: An Instrumental Album'' \n*Released: October 9, 2019\n|-\n|}\n\n===Soundtrack albums===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album details\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]]: Original Television Series Soundtrack'' \n*Released: January 19, 2018\n*Label: [[Hollywood Records]] \n|-\n|}\n\n===As featured artist===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=text-align:center;\n|-\n!style=\"width:3em\"| Year\n!|Song\n!| Album\n|-\n|2006\n| align=\"left\" | \"[[Oye Como Va]]\" \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[My Super Ex-Girlfriend]]: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack''\n|-\n|2008\n| align=\"left\" | \"The Rocker Score Suite\" \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[The Rocker: Music from the Motion Picture]]''\n|-\n|2009\n| align=\"left\" | \"[[Alone Again (Naturally)|Alone Again]]\" \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs]]: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack''\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2012\n| align=\"left\" | \"10 Years Score Suite\" \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[10 Years (2011 film)|10 Years]]: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack''\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | \"Chasing Mavericks Score Suite\" \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Chasing Mavericks#Soundtrack|Chasing Mavericks: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]''\n|-\n|}\n\n===Songs written and performed for films===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=text-align:center;\n|+ List of songs by Chad Fischer featured only in films and without a release anywhere else\n|-\n!style=\"width:3em\"| Year\n!|Song\n!| Film\n!| Notes\n|-\n|2001\n| align=\"left\" | \"Bright Shiny Theme Song\" \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Bubble Boy (film)|Bubble Boy]]''\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Written by Kevin Hunter & Chad Fischer. Performed by Chad Fischer, Kevin Hunter and Rachel Robinson\n|-\n|2002\n| align=\"left\" | \"See the Day\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[The First $20 Million Is Always the Hardest]]''\n|\n|-\n|2004\n| align=\"left\" | \"Motorcycle Ride with Sam\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Garden State (film)|Garden State]]''\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|Instrumental\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2005\n| align=\"left\" | \"Miserable Life\" \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[Little Manhattan]]''\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|Written and performed by Chad Fischer and [[Lyle Workman]]\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | \"Map of My Heart\" \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|Available to listen at Chad Fischer's [[Myspace]] page<ref name=Myspace/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2007\n| align=\"left\" | \"Come On\" \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Firehouse Dog]]''\n|\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | \"Bye Bye Bye\" \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[The Babysitters]]''\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|Written and performed by [[Sia Furler|Sia]] and Chad Fischer\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|2010\n| align=\"left\" | \"Frank & Beans\" \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Furry Vengeance]]''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|2012\n| align=\"left\" | \"O'Hare Air Jingle\" \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[The Lorax (film)|The Lorax]]''\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of music videos, showing year released\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Director\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Tomorrow Never Comes\"\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2008\n| Brooke Sasick\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Yosemite\"\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2019\n| rowspan=\"1\"| Colin Delehanty and Sheldon Neill\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Yellowstone\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Chad Fischer\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Craters of the Moon\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Shenandoah\"\n|\n|-\n|}\n;As director\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of music videos, showing year released\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Artist\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Send Somebody\"<ref>{{cite web | title = Colin Hay \u2013 Send Somebody | date = June 13, 2011 | url = https://vimeo.com/25064628 | via=Vimeo| accessdate = January 21, 2018}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2011\n| Colin Hay\n|-\n|}\n\n===With Lazlo Bane===\n;Studio albums\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album details\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[11 Transistor]]'' \n*Released: January 8, 1997\n*Label: [[Almo Sounds]] \n|-\n|2002\n|''[[All the Time in the World (Lazlo Bane album)|All the Time in the World]]''  \n*Released: September 27, 2002\n*Label: Self-released\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Back Sides]]'' \n*Released: April 11, 2006\n*Label: Self-released\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Guilty Pleasures (Lazlo Bane album)|Guitly Pleasures]]'' \n*Released: July 10, 2007\n*Label: Lookout Sound\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Big Spill (The Rage album)|Big Spill]]'' <br/><small>(The Rage)</small>\n*Released: April 23, 2013\n*Label: Lookout Mountain\n|}\n\n;EPs\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album details\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Short Style]]''\n*Released: August 20, 1996\n*Label: Almo Sounds\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Guilty Pleasures the 80's Volume 1]]''\n*Released: October 16, 2012\n*Label: Lookout Sound\n|}\n\n===With A Don Piper Situation===\n;EPs\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album details\n|-\n|1997\n|''A Don Piper Situation''\n*Released: 1997\n*Label: Scrimshaw Records\n|-\n|}\n\n===As producer, engineer, composer or session musician===\n{{Expand list|date=April 2016}}\n{{See also|Category:Albums produced by Chad Fischer}}\n{{See also|Category:Song recordings produced by Chad Fischer}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!style=\"width:3em\"|Year\n!style=\"width:18em\"|Subject\n!style=\"width:15em\"|Collaborator\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Comment\n|-\n| align=\"center\"|1994\n|''[[Topanga]]''\n|[[Colin Hay]]\n|drums, tambourine<ref name=almusic>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/chad-fischer-mn0000799766/credits|title= Chad Fischer credits|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=10 November 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\"|1995\n|''[[Sins of Our Fathers]]''\n|[[Andy Prieboy]]\n|drums, percussion, vocals\n|-\n| align=\"center\"|1996\n|''Xtended Play''\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Star 69 (band)|Star 69]]\n|song \"Girl from Mars\" recorded and mixed by Chad Fischer (also b-side to \"I'm Insane\" single)\"<ref name=almusic/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Star-69-Xtended-Play/release/6076336|title=Star 69 \u2013 Xtended Play|publisher=discogs|accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\"|1997\n|''Eating February''\n|song \"Rotten Punch\" recorded and mixed by Chad Fischer, also credited as additional musicican<ref name=almusic/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Star-69-Eating-February/release/1657735|title=Star 69 \u2013 Eating February|publisher=discogs|accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\"|1998\n|''[[Transcendental Highway]]''\n|[[Colin Hay]]\n|Drums, Percussion, Guitar, Backing Vocals<ref name=almusic/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Colin-Hay-Transcendental-Highway/release/1827363|title= Colin Hay \u2013 Transcendental Highway|publisher=discogs|accessdate=10 November 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\"|2000\n|''The Notorious One Man Orgy''\n|[[Josh Freese]]\n|recorded and mixed by Chad Fischer<ref na