 || 37,706 || 135,040 || align=\"right\"|1,244,758 || 8,703 || 39,268 ||62,036 || 16,325 || 425||126,757 ||align=\"right\"| 1,371,517 || 175,000 || na ||align=\"right\"|1,546,517\n|-\n!2017-18\n| 986,591 || 386 || 50,208 || 38,346 || 126,123 || align=\"right\"|1,201,653 || 5,056 || 25,871 || 52,666 || 15,252 || 358||101,839 ||align=\"right\"| 1,303,493 || 183,000 || na ||align=\"right\"|1,486,493\n|-\n!2016-17\n| 944,850 ||262 || 49,100 || 37,663 || 122,313 || align=\"right\"|1,154,188||7,673\n ||12,086  || 46,011  || 14,159 || 213 ||81,949 ||align=\"right\"| 1,236,137|| 197,000 || na ||align=\"right\"|1,433,392\n|-\n!2015-16\n| 896,260 ||406 || 47,122 || 37,413 || 121,377 || align=\"right\"|1,102,578||8,355\n || 7,450 ||  28,604 || 16,681 || 269 ||65,781 ||align=\"right\"| 1,168,359|| 183,611 || na ||align=\"right\"|1,351,970\n|-\n!2014-15\n| 835,838 || 1,407 || 41,075 || 36,102 || 129,244 || align=\"right\"|1,043,666||8,060\n || 4,600 || 28,214 || 14,944 || 414 ||61,780 ||align=\"right\"| 1,105,446|| 166,426 || na ||align=\"right\"|1,271,872\n|-\n!2013-14\n| 746,087 || 1,868 || 44,522 || 34,228 || 134,847 ||align=\"right\"|961,552 ||na || 3,350 || na || na || na ||59,615 ||align=\"right\"| 1,021,167|| 156,643|| na ||align=\"right\"|1,177,810\n|-\n!2012-13\n| 691,341 || 2,449 || 66,664|| 32,866 || 113,720 ||align=\"right\"|907,040 ||na || na || na || na ||na ||57,449 || align=\"right\"|964,489|| 144,009|| na ||align=\"right\"|1,108,498\n|-\n!2011-12\n|612,497 || 2,649 || 93,281 || 32,286 || 130,511 || align=\"right\"|871,224||na || na || na || na || na ||51,226 || align=\"right\"|922,451|| 134,387|| na ||align=\"right\"|1,056,838\n|}\n\nNotes: Coal includes lignite also; na \u2192 data not available;\n\nThe total generation from all renewable energy sources is nearly 15% of the total electricity generation (utility and captive) in India.\n\n==Energy conservation==\n{{See also |Negawatt power}}\n[[Energy conservation]] has emerged as a major policy objective, and the Energy Conservation Act 2001, was passed by the Indian Parliament in September 2001, 35.5% of the population still live without access to electricity. This Act requires large energy consumers to adhere to energy consumption norms; new buildings to follow the [[Energy Conservation Building Code]]; and appliances to meet energy performance standards and to display energy consumption labels. The Act also created the Bureau of Energy Efficiency to implement the provisions of the Act. In 2015, Prime Minister Mr. Modi launched a scheme called \n[[Bachat Lamp Yojna|Prakash Path]] urging people to use [[LED lamps]] in place of other lamps to drastically cut down lighting power requirement. Energy efficient fans at subsidised price are offered to the electricity consumers by the electricity distribution companies (DisComs) to decrease peak electricity load.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2016-01-20/news/69931198_1_eesl-fans-ceiling|title= Andhra Pradesh to replace 1 Lakh ceiling fans with energy-efficient ones|accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Rural electrification==\n{{See|Rural Electrification Corporation Limited}}\nAs on 28 April 2018, all Indian villages were electrified.<ref>{{cite web|title=India says electrified all villages ahead of prime minister's deadline  |url=https://energy.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/power/india-says-electrified-all-villages-ahead-of-prime-ministers-deadline/63962206|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref> India has achieved 100% electrification of all rural and urban households. As of 4 January 2019, 211.88 million rural households are provided with electricity, which is nearly 100% of the 212.65 million total rural households.<ref name=\"hhe\">{{cite web|url=http://saubhagya.gov.in/|title=Households electrification in India| accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref> Up to 4 January 2019, 42.937 million urban households are provided with electricity, which is almost 100% of the 42.941 million total urban households. 89% of house holds in the country use LPG drastically reducing the use of traditional fuels \u2013 [[Firewood|fuelwood]], agricultural waste and [[Dry animal dung fuel|biomass cakes]] \u2013 for cooking and general heating needs.<ref name=cook>{{cite web|  url=https://energy.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/oil-and-gas/lpg-cylinder-now-used-by-89-households/66930301 |title= LPG cylinder now used by 89% households |accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break|width=35%}}\n*[[Electricity sector in India]]\n*[[Energy in India]]\n*[[Economics of new nuclear power plants]]\n*[[Levelised energy cost]]\n*[[Energy returned on energy invested]]\n*[[East West Gas Pipeline (India)|Reliance east to west India gas pipeline]]\n*[[Coal slurry pipeline]]\n* [[Yarlung Tsangpo Grand Canyon|40,000 MW Yarlung Tsangpo Hydroelectric Project]]\n*[[Negawatt power]]\n{{col-break|width=25%}}\n*[[Water Resources in India]]\n*[[Indian Rivers Inter-link]]\n*[[Bioeconomy]]\n*[[Biomass to liquid]]\n*[[Gas to liquid]]\n*[[Coal to liquid]]\n*[[Torrefaction]]\n*[[Low-carbon economy]]\n*[[Energy cannibalism]]\n{{col-break|width=25%}}\n*[[Fossil fuel phase-out]]\n*[[Renewable natural gas]]\n*[[Algae fuel]]\n*[[Solar power in India]]\n*[[Wind power in India]]\n*[[Renewable energy in India]]\n*[[Index of energy articles]]\n*[[Index of solar energy articles]]\n*[[List of energy abbreviations]]\n{{col-break}}\n{{Portal|Energy|India}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160308010516/http://www.idatainsights.com/reports-landing-page.php?id=252%2Findian-energy-and-infrastructure-policy-handbook  Ready Reference Policy Handbook about India at one place]\n*[http://indianpowersector.com/  Latest news about Indian Power Sector at one place]\n*[http://www.openpr.com/news/173204/Highlights-of-Rajasthan-Solar-Policy-2011-explained-by-Headway-Solar.html Highlights of Rajasthan Solar Policy 2011]\n* [http://www.openpr.com/news/180803/Range-of-Rural-Solar-Home-Lighting-Systems-launched-by-Headway-Solar-in-India.html Solar to light up Rural India]\n*[http://www.oilandgasinfrastructure.com/home/oilandgasasia/oilandgasindia Map of oil and gas infrastructure (incomplete)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140323094317/http://www.newsyaps.com/indias-river-linking-scheme-a-case-of-troubled-waters/102486 India's River-Linking Scheme: A case of troubled waters]\n\n{{Nuclear power in India}}\n{{India topics}}\n{{Asia topic|Energy policy of}}\n{{Policies of India}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Energy Policy Of India}}\n[[Category:Energy in India]]\n[[Category:Energy policy by country|India]]\n[[Category:Energy policy in Asia|India]]\n[[Category:Policies of India]]\n", "name_user": "Strickesel", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed a typo found byWikipedia:Typo Team/moss\u2013 you can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Energy_policy_of_India"}
{"title_page": "Beverley McLachlin", "text_new": "{{redirect|McLachlin|the surname|McLachlin (surname)}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Beverley McLachlin\n| honorific-suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|PC|CC|size=100%}} [[Order of Saint John (chartered 1888)|CStJ]]\n| image = Beverley McLachlin (crop).jpg\n| imagesize = \n| smallimage = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| office = Non-Permanent Judge of the [[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Final Appeal of Hong Kong]]\n| term_label = \n| term_start = July 30, 2018\n| term_end = \n| nominator = \n| appointer = [[Carrie Lam]]\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| office2 = 17th [[Chief Justice of Canada]]\n| term_start2 = January 7, 2000\n| term_end2 = December 15, 2017\n| monarch2 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| nominator2 = [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]]\n| primeminister2 = {{plainlist|\n* [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]]\n* [[Paul Martin]]\n* [[Stephen Harper]]\n* [[Justin Trudeau]]\n}}\n| appointer2 = [[Adrienne Clarkson]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Antonio Lamer]]\n| successor2 = [[Richard Wagner (judge)|Richard Wagner]]\n| 1blankname2 = {{nowrap|Governor General}}\n| 1namedata2 = {{plainlist|\n* [[Adrienne Clarkson]]\n* [[Micha\u00eblle Jean]]\n* [[David Johnston]]\n* [[Julie Payette]]\n}}\n| office3 = [[Puisne Justice]] of the [[Supreme Court of Canada]]\n| term_start3 = March 30, 1989\n| term_end3 = January 7, 2000\n| nominator3 = [[Brian Mulroney]]\n| appointer3 = [[Jeanne Sauv\u00e9]]\n| predecessor3 = [[William McIntyre (judge)|William McIntyre]]\n| successor3 = [[Louis LeBel]]\n| office4 = Chief Justice of the [[Supreme Court of British Columbia]]\n| term_start4 = 1988\n| term_end4= 1990\n| nominator4 = \n| appointer4 = [[Jeanne Sauv\u00e9]]\n| predecessor4 = \n| successor4 = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1943|9|7}}\n| birth_place = [[Pincher Creek]], [[Alberta]], Canada\n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| restingplace = \n| restingplacecoordinates = \n| birthname = Beverley Gietz\n| citizenship = Canadian\n| nationality = \n| party = \n| otherparty = <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n| spouse = {{plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Roderick McLachlin|1967|1988|end=died}}\n* {{marriage|Frank McArdle|1992}}\n}}\n| partner = <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations = \n| children = Angus McLachlin (b. 1976)\n| parents = \n| residence = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Alberta]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = Judge\n| cabinet = \n| committees = \n| portfolio = \n| religion = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Beverley Marian McLachlin''', {{post-nominals|country=CAN|PC|CC|[[Order of Saint John (chartered 1888)|CStJ]]}} {{Small|[[Order of Saint John (chartered 1888)|CStJ]]}} (born September 7, 1943) is a Canadian jurist and author who served as the 17th [[Chief Justice of Canada]] from 2000 to 2017, the first woman to hold that position and the longest-serving chief justice in Canadian history. In her role as chief justice, she also simultaneously served as a [[Deputy of the Governor General of Canada]].\n\nMcLachlin retired December 15, 2017, nine months before reaching the mandatory retirement age of 75.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2017/06/12/chief-justice-beverley-mclachlin-to-step-down-from-supreme-court-of-canada.html| title=Chief Justice Beverley McLachlin to retire from Supreme Court of Canada| first=Tonda| last=MacCharles| date=June 12, 2017| work=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref> Her successor as Chief Justice of Canada is [[Richard Wagner (judge)|Richard Wagner]], who was nominated by Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite press release| title=Prime Minister names the Honourable Richard Wagner as new Chief Justice of Canada| url=https://pm.gc.ca/eng/news/2017/12/12/prime-minister-names-honourable-richard-wagner-new-chief-justice-canada| website=pm.gc.ca| publisher=[[Office of the Prime Minister (Canada)|PMO]]| accessdate=December 12, 2017|language=en|date=December 12, 2017}}</ref> Her successor as a justice of the court is [[Sheilah Martin]], who was nominated by Prime Minister Justin Trudeau through a new process for judicial appointments to the Supreme Court of Canada that permitted, \"any Canadian lawyer or judge who fits a specified criteria\" to apply.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/why-canada-has-a-new-way-to-choose-supreme-court-judges/article31220275/| title=Why Canada has a new way to choose Supreme Court judges| date=August 2, 2016| accessdate=April 24, 2017| author=[[Justin Trudeau]]| website=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release| url=http://pm.gc.ca/eng/news/2016/08/02/new-process-judicial-appointments-supreme-court-canada| title=New process for judicial appointments to the Supreme Court of Canada| date=August 2, 2016| publisher=[[Government of Canada]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=Prime Minister announces nomination of the Honourable Sheilah L. Martin to the Supreme Court of Canada|date=November 29, 2017|publisher=[[Office of the Prime Minister (Canada)|PMO]]|url=https://pm.gc.ca/eng/news/2017/11/29/prime-minister-announces-nomination-honourable-sheilah-l-martin-supreme-court-canada|website=pm.gc.ca}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, McLachlin was nominated to become a non-permanent judge on the [[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal]], the first Canadian jurist nominated to the post.<ref>[https://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201803/21/P2018032100305.htm Appointment of non-permanent judges from other common law jurisdictions of the Court of Final Appeal]</ref> The appointment was gazetted and came into effect July 30, 2018, for a three-year term.<ref>[https://www.gld.gov.hk/egazette/pdf/20182231/egn201822315815.pdf Hong Kong Gazette Notice GN5815/2018]</ref>\n\n==Early life and family==\nMcLachlin was born Beverley Gietz in [[Pincher Creek]], [[Alberta]], the eldest child of Eleanora Marian (n\u00e9e Kruschell) and Ernest Gietz. Her parents, who were of German descent, were \"[[fundamentalist Christians]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/447043341.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jan+19%2C+2000&author=&pub=The+Spectator&desc='Justice+lies+at+the+heart+of+what+Canada+is'&pqatl=google |title='Justice lies at the heart of what Canada is' |website=Pqasb.pqarchiver.com |date= |accessdate=2016-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-F_gyzny_XgC&pg=PT201&dq=Beverley+Gietz |title=Mighty Judgment: How The Supreme Court Of Canada Runs Your Life |author=Philip Slayton |website=Books.google.ca |date=1943-09-07 |accessdate=2016-02-17|isbn=9780143180517 }}</ref> of the [[Pentecostal Church]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/religious-upbringing-influences-chief-justice/article1039974/| title=Religious upbringing influences Chief Justice| first=Canadian| last=Press| date=May 25, 2000| work=[[Globe & Mail]]}}</ref> She received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] and an [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] in [[philosophy]] as well as an [[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]] degree (winning the gold medal as top student, and serving as editor-in-chief of the ''[[Alberta Law Review]]'') from the [[University of Alberta]]. She was called to the [[Law Society of Alberta|Bar of Alberta]] in 1969, and to the [[Law Society of British Columbia|Bar of British Columbia]] in 1971. McLachlin practised law from 1969 until 1975. From 1974 to 1981, she was an associate professor and professor with [[tenure]] at the [[University of British Columbia]].\n\nMcLachlin has one son, Angus (born 1976), from her first [[marriage]] to Roderick McLachlin, who took care of much of Angus's upbringing.<ref name=np23/> Roderick McLachlin died of cancer in 1988, a few days after she was appointed chief justice of the B.C. Supreme Court.<ref name=np23/> In 1992, McLachlin married Frank McArdle, a lawyer and the executive director of the Canadian Superior Courts Judges Association.<ref name=np23/>\n\n==Judicial career==\n===Canada===\nIn April 1981, McLachlin was appointed to the [[Counties of British Columbia#County Courts|County Court]] of [[Vancouver]]. Five months later, in September 1981, she was appointed to the [[Supreme Court of British Columbia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scc-csc.ca/judges-juges/bio-eng.aspx?id=beverley-mclachlin|title=Supreme Court of Canada - Biography - Beverley McLachlin|last=Canada|first=Supreme Court of|date=2001-01-01|website=www.scc-csc.ca|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref> In December 1985, McLachlin was appointed to the [[British Columbia Court of Appeal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scc-csc.ca/judges-juges/bio-eng.aspx?id=beverley-mclachlin|title=Supreme Court of Canada - Biography - Beverley McLachlin|last=Canada|first=Supreme Court of|date=2001-01-01|website=www.scc-csc.ca|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref> In September 1988, McLachlin was appointed Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of British Columbia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scc-csc.ca/judges-juges/bio-eng.aspx?id=beverley-mclachlin|title=Supreme Court of Canada - Biography - Beverley McLachlin|last=Canada|first=Supreme Court of|date=2001-01-01|website=www.scc-csc.ca|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref> She was nominated by [[Brian Mulroney]] to be made a Puisne Justice to the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] on March 30, 1989.<ref name=np23/> On the advice of [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]], McLachlin was appointed the Chief Justice of Canada on January 7, 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scc-csc.ca/judges-juges/bio-eng.aspx?id=beverley-mclachlin|title=Supreme Court of Canada - Biography - Beverley McLachlin|first=Supreme Court of|last=Canada|date=January 1, 2001|publisher=}}</ref> \n\nUpon being sworn into the [[Supreme Court of Canada]], she also became a [[Deputy of the Governor General of Canada]] together with the other justices of the Supreme Court.\n\nWhen [[Governor General of Canada|Governor General]] [[Adrienne Clarkson]] was hospitalized for a [[cardiac pacemaker]] operation on July 8, 2005, McLachlin performed the duties of the governor general as the [[administrator of Canada]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title = Canada\u2019s Chief Justice lays down the law {{!}} The Journal|url = http://www.queensjournal.ca/story/2006-01-17/features/canadas-chief-justice-lays-down-law/|website = www.queensjournal.ca|accessdate = 2015-10-13}}</ref> In her role as administrator, she gave [[royal assent]] to the ''[[Civil Marriage Act]]'' which legalized [[same-sex marriage in Canada|same-sex marriage nationally in Canada]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She relinquished that task when the governor general returned to good health in late July.\n\nMcLachlin is the chairperson of the [[Canadian Judicial Council]], on the board of governors of the National Judicial Institute, and on the advisory council of the [[Order of Canada]]. She is a Member of the [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada]]. McLachlin was made a Commander of the [[Legion of Honour]] by the Government of France in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazette.gc.ca/archives/p1/2007/2007-11-24/pdf/g1-14147.pdf|format=PDF|title=Canada Gazette Part I|volume=141, No. 47|website=Gazette.gc.ca|accessdate=2016-02-17|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130522213038/http://www.gazette.gc.ca/archives/p1/2007/2007-11-24/pdf/g1-14147.pdf|archivedate=May 22, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ambafrance-ca.org/spip.php?article1876&var_recherche=Beverley%20McLachlin|title=La France d\u00e9core la Juge en chef du Canada|work=La France au Canada/France in Canada}}</ref> On December 15, 2006, she was appointed Commander of the [[Venerable Order of Saint John]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazette.gc.ca/archives/p1/2007/2007-04-28/pdf/g1-14117.pdf|format=PDF|title=Canada Gazette Part I,|volume=141, No. 17|website=Gazette.gc.ca|accessdate=2016-02-17|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130522213631/http://www.gazette.gc.ca/archives/p1/2007/2007-04-28/pdf/g1-14117.pdf|archivedate=May 22, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nMcLachlin has defined her function as one that requires ''conscious objectivity'', which she describes as follows:<ref name=np23>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/conscious-objectivity-thats-how-the-chief-justice-defines-the-top-courts-role-harper-might-beg-to-differ |title=\u2018Conscious objectivity\u2019: That\u2019s how the chief justice defines the top court\u2019s role. Harper might beg to differ &#124; National Post |website=News.nationalpost.com |date= |accessdate=2016-02-17}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|What you have to try to do as a judge, whether you're on charter issues or any other issue, is by an act of the imagination put yourself in the shoes of the different parties, and think about how it looks from their perspective, and really think about it, not just give it lip service&nbsp;...\n\nAs a judge, and I've been a judge for a long time, I have always resolved to just try to judge the issues as honestly as I can, and not to think about things in too strategic a manner. My job is simply to listen to what the parties have to say, and to do my best to understand the position, the ramifications of deciding one way or the other, to think about what\u2019s best for Canadian society on this particular problem that\u2019s before us, and give it my best judgment after listening to, also, my eight other colleagues. So there's a consensual element there.}}\n\nMcLachlin has stated, \"I think the court belongs to the Canadian people and it should reflect the Canadian people.\" In the opinion of an interviewer, this is \"not only to convey an impression of balance, but to bring in perspectives that were so long absent from the judicial imagination. To her, judgment is not a coldly neutral evaluation of competing positions, robotically free of passion or perspective. It is an engaged, human act of imagination.\"<ref name=np23/>\n\nThe Supreme Court, under McLachlin, ruled against the former Conservative government of [[Stephen Harper]] on several important issues, including prostitution, assisted dying, mandatory minimum gun crime sentences, Senate reform, whether [[Taliban]] fighter [[Omar Khadr]] deserved an adult sentence, and whether Federal Court judge [[Marc Nadon]] could be elevated to the Supreme Court.<ref name=np23/>\n\nIn July 2013, during the consultation period prior to appointment for [[Marc Nadon]], Chief Justice McLachlin contacted justice minister [[Peter MacKay]] and the [[Office of the Prime Minister (Canada)|Prime Minister's Office]] regarding the eligibility of [[Marc Nadon]] for a Quebec seat on the Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scc-csc.lexum.com/scc-csc/news/en/item/4602/index.do|title=News Release - SCC Cases (Lexum)|date=|website=Scc-csc.lexum.com|accessdate=2016-02-17}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Stephen Harper]] stated that he had refused a phone call from McLachlin on the attorney general's advice. Harper's comments were criticized by the legal community and a complaint was forwarded to the [[International Commission of Jurists]] in Switzerland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2014/05/02/stephen_harper_lashes_out_at_top_judge_on_supreme_court.html|title=Stephen Harper lashes out at top judge on Supreme Court|date=May 2, 2014|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2014/05/13/canadas_legal_community_steps_up_its_demand_that_stephen_harper_withdraw_criticism_of_chief_justice.html|title=Legal community demands Stephen Harper withdraw criticism of Beverley McLachlin|date=May 13, 2014|newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref>  The [[International Commission of Jurists]] concluded that Beverly McLachlin deserved an apology from Harper, but none had been given as of July 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/m/news/politics/beverley-mclachlin-chief-justice-deserves-apology-from-pm-international-jurists-say-1.2718342|title=International Commission of Jurists demands Stephen Harper apologize to Beverley McLachlin|date=July 25, 2014|newspaper=CBC News}}</ref>As of May 20, 2019, no apology has been given. (Conversation with Beverley McLachlin on AC 345)\n\nMcLachlin surpassed Sir [[William Johnstone Ritchie]] as the longest-serving Chief Justice of Canada in history on September 22, 2013.\n\nIn May 2015, McLachlin was invited to speak at the [[Global Centre for Pluralism]], and said that Canada attempted to commit \"[[cultural genocide]]\" against aboriginal peoples in what she called the worst stain on Canada's human-rights record.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/chief-justice-says-canada-attempted-cultural-genocide-on-aboriginals/article24688854/|title=Chief Justice says Canada attempted 'cultural genocide' on aboriginals|author=Canada|date=|accessdate=2016-02-17|publisher=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> University of Regina academic [[Ken Coates (historian)|Ken Coates]] was quick to support McLachlin, and said that she was \"only stating what is clearly in the minds of judges, lawyers and aboriginal people across the country\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-debate/mclachlin-said-what-many-have-long-known/article24704812/|title=McLachlin said what many have long known|author=Ken Coates|date=|accessdate=2016-02-17|publisher=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>\n\nOthers were far less sympathetic. Columnist [[Lysiane Gagnon]] called the comments \"unacceptable\" and \"highly inflammatory\" and suggested that McLachlin had opened herself up to accusations of prejudice.<ref name=\"LG\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-debate/mclachlins-comments-a-disservice-to-her-court-and-to-aboriginals/article24879482/|title=McLachlin\u2019s comments a disservice to her court, and to aboriginals|last1=Lysiane|first1=Gagnon|date=June 10, 2015|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|accessdate=June 10, 2015}}</ref> [[Gordon Gibson]], another columnist, said the use of the word \"genocide\" was incendiary and disproportionate and that the Chief Justice's comments made her sound like a legislator.<ref name=\"GG\">{{cite news|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/full-comment/gordon-gibson-it-is-bad-for-democracy-when-nine-unelected-people-can-make-law|title=It is bad for democracy when nine unelected people can make law|last1=Gibson|first1=Gordon|date=June 10, 2015|work=National Post|accessdate=June 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Hong Kong===\n\nMcLachlin was nominated in March 2018 to become a non-permanent member of the [[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Final Appeal]] in [[Hong Kong]]. The Court appoints foreign judges from [[common-law]] jurisdictions outside of Hong Kong, of which McLachlin is the first Canadian, to sit as non-permanent members of the court.<ref name=\"HK\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-beverley-mclachlin-nominated-for-hong-kongs-top-court/|title=Former chief justice Beverley McLachlin nominated for Hong Kong\u2019s top court|date=March 21, 2018|work=Globe and Mail|accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref> Her appointment was approved by the [[Hong Kong Legislative Council]],<ref name=\"legco approval\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/2143767/pro-beijing-lawmakers-speak-out-against-two-female-foreign|title=Pro-Beijing lawmakers voice concerns over foreign judges' support for gay rights|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref> and the chief executive gazetted the appointment effective July 30, 2018. McLachlin's appointment was accompanied by the ones of [[Brenda Hale, Baroness Hale of Richmond|Baroness Hale of Richmond]], also as non-permanent judge, and [[Andrew Cheung|Mr Justice Cheung]], as permanent judge, at the court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201803/21/P2018032100305.htm|title=Appointment of non-permanent judges from other common law jurisdictions of the Court of Final Appeal|website=www.info.gov.hk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-crime/article/2138271/two-female-foreign-judges-appointed-hong-kongs-top-court|title=Hong Kong\u2019s top court gets two female foreign judges in historic first|publisher=}}</ref> In the same year, she published a legal thriller novel entitled ''Full Disclosure''.<ref>[https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/books/2018/05/11/how-beverley-mclachlin-wrote-her-first-thriller-while-holding-a-full-time-job-as-chief-justice-of-canada.html \"How Beverley McLachlin wrote her first thriller while holding a full-time job as Chief Justice of Canada\"]. ''[[Toronto Star]]'', May 11, 2018.</ref>\n\n==Judgments==\n{{Main|Reasons of the Supreme Court of Canada by Chief Justice McLachlin}}\nDuring her early years on the Supreme Court, she was characterized as a judge with libertarian leaning after her dissent in ''[[R v Keegstra]]'', finding that the hate-speech criminal offences were unconstitutional, and her judgment in ''[[R v Zundel]]'' where she struck down the criminal offence of spreading false news. This was also seen to an extent in her decision of ''[[R v Sharpe]]'' where she upheld the child pornography criminal provisions, but limited it by excluding imaginative works that are for private use. During this, she also ruled that the laws should apply to fictional depictions, declaring that 'person' would include fictional people as well as real people:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scc.lexum.umontreal.ca/en/2001/2001scc2/2001scc2.html |accessdate=April 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430210752/http://scc.lexum.umontreal.ca/en/2001/2001scc2/2001scc2.html |title=Supreme Court of Canada - Decisions - R. v. Sharpe |archivedate=April 30, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Interpreting \"person\" in accordance with Parliament's purpose of criminalizing possession of material that poses a reasoned risk of harm to children, it seems that it should include visual works of the imagination as well as depictions of actual people. Notwithstanding the fact that 'person' in the charging section and in s. 163.1(1)(b) refers to a flesh-and-blood person, I conclude that \"person\" in s. 163.1(1)(a) includes both actual and imaginary human beings. |[[Supreme Court of Canada]]|''[[R v Sharpe]]'', Paragraph 38}}\n\nAmong her more controversial decisions was her ruling in ''[[R v Seaboyer]]'', in which she struck down the [[rape shield law]] because it violated the right to a fair trial of those accused of sexual assault.\n\nMcLachlin has tried to forge additional consensus in the court's decisions, often writing controversial decisions herself to forge that consensus. In doing so, she is widely recognized for \"still writing lots of judgments in her own clear style\".<ref>[http://thechronicleherald.ca/Front/1150605.html]{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nThe Supreme Court [[Carter v. Canada|unanimously ruled]] on February 6, 2015, that the prohibition on [[Euthanasia in Canada|assisted suicide]] was unconstitutional and overturned its own prior decision on the subject from 1993, ''[[Rodriguez v British Columbia (AG)]]''. McLachlin wrote the dissent in the 1993 case and was the only justice from that era remaining on the court in 2015.<ref>{{cite web\n|last=Macfarlane\n|first=Emmett\n|title=On assisted suicide, the Supreme Court confronts Parliament\u2019s cowardice\n|date=February 6, 2015\n|publisher=[[Maclean's]]\n|url=http://www.macleans.ca/politics/on-assisted-suicide-the-supreme-court-confronts-parliaments-cowardice/\n|accessdate=February 6, 2015\n}}</ref>\n\n==Honorary degrees and other awards==\n\nShe is the Honorary Patron of the [[Institute of Parliamentary and Political Law]]. She has also been awarded the ''Yes She Can Award'' from [[Balmoral Hall School]] in 2005. She is currently the Visitor of [[Massey College]], an interdisciplinary graduate college for students of distinguished ability at the [[University of Toronto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.masseycollege.ca/about/governance/|title=Governance \u2013 Massey College|website=www.masseycollege.ca|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref>. In 2017 she was elected Visitor of Queens' College, Cambridge. She has been awarded with over 31 [[honorary degree]]s from various universities, which include:\n\n{| border=\"1\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:100%; margin:0.5em 1em 0.5em 0; border:1px #056 solid; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|-\n|+ Honorary degrees\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Location</span>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Date</span>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:40%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">School</span>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Degree</span>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|British Columbia}} || '''27 September 1990''' || [[University of British Columbia]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.library.ubc.ca/archives/honchron.html |title=University of British Columbia Library - University Archives |website=Library.ubc.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.library.ubc.ca/archives/hdcites/hdcites9.html#mclachlin |title=UBC Archives - Honorary Degree Citations - 1989-1991 |website=Library.ubc.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-02-17}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Alberta}} || '''1991''' || [[University of Alberta]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D.)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.senate.ualberta.ca/HonoraryDegrees/PastHonoraryDegreeRecipients.aspx |title=Past Honorary Degree Recipients - University of Alberta |website=Senate.ualberta.ca |accessdate=2016-02-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304185921/http://www.senate.ualberta.ca/HonoraryDegrees/PastHonoraryDegreeRecipients.aspx |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Ontario}} || '''June 1995''' || [[University of Toronto]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.governingcouncil.utoronto.ca/Assets/Governing+Council+Digital+Assets/Boards+and+Committees/Committee+for+Honorary+Degrees/degreerecipients1850tillnow.pdf |format=PDF |title=Honorary Degree Recipients |website=Governingcouncil.utoronto.ca |accessdate=2016-02-17}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Ontario}} || '''Spring 1999''' || [[York University]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D.)<ref>{{cite web |author=Current Students |url=http://secretariat.info.yorku.ca/senate/sub-committee-on-honorary-degrees-and-ceremonials/honorary-degree-recipients/ |title=Honorary Degree Recipients &#124; University Secretariat |website=Secretariat.info.yorku.ca |accessdate=2016-02-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150318112748/http://secretariat.info.yorku.ca/senate/sub-committee-on-honorary-degrees-and-ceremonials/honorary-degree-recipients/ |archivedate=March 18, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Ontario}} || '''2000''' || [[Law Society of Upper Canada]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lsuc.on.ca/with.aspx?id=762 |title=Honorary LLD &#124; The Law Society of Upper Canada |website=Lsuc.on.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-02-17}}</ref>  \n|-\n| {{Flagu|British Columbia}} || '''2000''' || [[Simon Fraser University]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D.)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfu.ca/ceremonies/honorary-degrees/past_honorary_degrees.html |title=Past Honorary Degree Recipients - Ceremonies and Events - Simon Fraser University |website=Sfu.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-02-17}}</ref>  \n|-\n| {{Flagu|Alberta}} || '''2000''' || [[University of Calgary]] ||<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucalgary.ca/pubs/calendar/current/who-honorary-degree-recipients.html |title=University of Calgary : Honorary Degree Recipients |website=Ucalgary.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-02-17}}</ref>  \n|-\n| {{Flagu|Ontario}} || '''2000''' || [[University of Ottawa]] || [[Doctor of the University]] (D.Univ.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.media.uottawa.ca/mediaroom/awards-recipients_153.html |accessdate=May 1, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091102195820/http://www.media.uottawa.ca/mediaroom/awards-recipients_153.html |archivedate=November 2, 2009 |title=Distinguished Canadian Leadership Award (DCLA) &#124; Awards & Achievements &#124; Media Room}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uottawa.ca/president/people/mclaughlin-beverly#Array |title=McLAUGHLIN, Beverly &#124; Office of the President &#124; University of Ottawa |website=Uottawa.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-02-17}}</ref>  \n|-\n| {{Flagu|Ontario}} || '''8 June 2000''' || [[Brock University]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D.)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://brocku.ca/webfm_send/33360 |format=PDF |title=BROCK UNIVERSITY HONORARY DEGREE AND AWARD RECIPIENTS |website=Brocku.ca |accessdate=2016-02-17}}</ref>  \n|-\n| {{Flagu|British Columbia}} || '''November 2000''' || [[University of Victoria]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D.)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uvic.ca/universitysecretary/senate/honorary/recipients/ |title=University of Victoria -Honorary degree recipients - University of Victoria |website=Uvic.ca |date=2015-12-08 |accessdate=2016-02-17}}</ref>  \n|-\n| {{Flagu|Alberta}} || '''Spring 2001''' || [[University of Lethbridge]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D.)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uleth.ca/governance/sites/governance/files/UofL%20Honorary%20Degree%20Recipients%20August%202014.pdf |format=PDF |title=Honorary Degree Recipients |website=Uleth.ca |accessdate=2016-02-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150428031927/