{"title_page": "I Love Rock 'n' Roll", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Short description|1975 rock single}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Love Rock 'n' Roll\n| cover      = Arrows I Love Rock n Roll.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = 2004 re-issue\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Arrows (British band)|Arrows]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = [[Broken Down Heart]]\n| released   = July 1975\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 1975\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hard rock]]\n| length     = 2:48\n| label      = [[RAK Records|RAK]]\n| writer     = [[Alan Merrill]], [[Jake Hooker (musician)|Jake Hooker]]\n| producer   = [[Mickie Most]]\n| prev_title = Hard Hearted\n| prev_year  = 1975\n| next_title = Once Upon a Time\n| next_year  = 1976\n}}\n\n\"'''I Love Rock 'n' Roll'''\" is a [[Rock music|rock]] song written by [[Alan Merrill]] and [[Jake Hooker (musician)|Jake Hooker]] and first recorded by the [[Arrows (British band)|Arrows]] in 1975. It is best known for its 1982 cover version by [[Joan Jett|Joan Jett & the Blackhearts]], which was released as the first single from her [[I Love Rock 'n Roll (album)|album of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Cad|first=Saint|title=10 More Famous Songs With Unknown Originals|url=http://listverse.com/2012/10/14/10-more-famous-songs-with-unknown-originals/|work=listverse.com|accessdate=21 June 2013}}</ref> Jett's rendition became her highest-charting hit, reaching number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100]] and becoming the [[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1982|No. 3 song for 1982]]. The single was certified platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]], representing two million units shipped to stores. Jett's version was inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/press-release/the-recording-academy-announces-2016-grammy-hall-of-fame-inductees|title=The Recording Academy Announces 2016 Grammy Hall of Fame Inductees|work=Recording Academy|accessdate=February 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Arrows original version==\nThe song was originally recorded and [[release (music)|released]] by [[Arrows (British band)|Arrows]] in 1975 on [[Rak Records]], with Merrill on lead vocals and guitar and [[Mickie Most]] producing. Merrill wrote the music and lyrics. In an interview with Songfacts, Merrill said he wrote the song as \"a knee-jerk response to [[the Rolling Stones]]' '[[It's Only Rock 'n Roll (But I Like It)]]'.\"<ref name=\"Outsight Radio Hours interview\">{{cite web|title=Outsight Radio Hours interview, 12 February 2012|url=https://archive.org/details/AlanMerrillOnOutsightRadioHours|accessdate=18 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"songfacts\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=2422 \n |title=I Love Rock and Roll \n |work=Songfacts.com \n |accessdate=2009-09-20 \n |url-status=dead \n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226214725/http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=2422 \n |archive-date=26 February 2017 \n |df= \n}}</ref>\nThis version was first released as a [[B-side]], but was soon re-recorded and flipped to [[A-side]] status on a subsequent pressing of the record. Arrows performed the song in 1975 on the [[Muriel Young]]-produced show ''45'', after which Young offered Arrows a weekly UK television series, ''[[Arrows (TV series)|Arrows]]'', which was broadcast on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] starting in March 1976.<ref name=\"Cover song\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-29568083 \"Ten hits you may not know were cover versions\"]. BBC News. Retrieved 14 October 2014</ref>\n\n==Joan Jett version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Love Rock 'n Roll\n| cover      = File:I Love Rock n Roll by Joan Jett and the Blackheads US vinyl single.png\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Artwork for US and Australian edition\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Joan Jett|Joan Jett and the Blackhearts]]\n| album      = [[I Love Rock 'n Roll (album)|I Love Rock 'n Roll]]\n| B-side     = \"You Don't Know What You've Got\" or \"Love is Pain\"\n| released   = January 19, 1982\n| format     = [[7-inch single]], [[12-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 1981\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hard rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.allmusic.com/song/i-love-rock-n-roll-mt0010368331 |first= Steve |last= Huey |title= I Love Rock N' Roll \u2013 Song Review |work= [[AllMusic|Allmusic]] |publisher= [[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate= February 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title= Rock Obituaries - Knocking On Heaven's Door |first= Nick |last= Talevski\n|publisher= [[Music Sales Group|Omnibus Press]] |quote= Cordell joined [[Kenny Laguna]], his former session player and then manager of Joan Jett & the Blackhearts, to co-produce the group's chart-topping hard-rock anthem 'I Love Rock 'N Roll'. |year= 2006 |page= 100 |isbn= 978-1-8460-9091-2}}</ref>\n| length     = 2:55 (LP version) 2:45 (U.S. single edit)\n| label      = [[Boardwalk Records|Boardwalk]]\n| writer     = [[Alan Merrill]], [[Jake Hooker (musician)|Jake Hooker]]\n| producer   = [[Ritchie Cordell]], [[Kenny Laguna]]\n| prev_title = [[Bad Reputation (Joan Jett song)|Bad Reputation]]\n| prev_year  = 1981\n| next_title = [[Crimson and Clover#Joan Jett version|Crimson and Clover]]\n| next_year  = 1982\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|t5ecqUhec-s|\"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" (''TopPop'', 1982)}}}}\n}}\n{{listen\n|filename=I Love Rock N Roll sample.ogg\n|title=\"I Love Rock N Roll\"\n|description=[[Joan Jett|Joan Jett and the Blackhearts]]' \"I Love Rock N Roll\" from ''[[I Love Rock 'n Roll (album)|I Love Rock 'n Roll]]''\n|filetype=[[Ogg]]}}\n\n[[Joan Jett]] saw the [[Arrows (British band)|Arrows]] perform \"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" on their weekly UK television series ''[[Arrows (TV series)|Arrows]]''<ref name=\"Outsight Radio Hours interview\"/> while she was touring England with [[the Runaways]] in 1976.<ref name=\"Cover song\"/> She first recorded the song in 1979 with two of the [[Sex Pistols]], [[Steve Jones (musician)|Steve Jones]] and [[Paul Cook]]. This first version was released on vinyl in 1979 on Vertigo records as a B-side to \"[[You Don't Own Me]]\". In 1981, Jett re-recorded the song, this time with her band, [[the Blackhearts]]. This recording became a U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] number-one single for seven weeks.<ref>[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]] (2004). ''The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits'', 8th Edition (Billboard Publications), page 322.</ref>\n\n===Music video===\nThe black-and-white [[music video]] for \"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" received heavy play by the fledgling [[MTV]] network. It featured Jett and the Blackhearts traveling to a small, dingy bar and then exciting the drunken crowd by performing the song and yelling out its [[refrain|chorus]]. A snippet of Jett's 1981 hit \"[[Bad Reputation (Joan Jett song)|Bad Reputation]]\" can be heard at the beginning of the video. The video was originally in color, but it was converted to black and white because Jett hated the look of her red leather jumpsuit in color.<ref>{{Citation|title=Joan Jett & the Blackhearts: I Love Rock 'n' Roll (Video 1982)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6973600/trivia|accessdate=2018-12-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993 Joan Jett & the Blackhearts made another music video for the song as part of the ''[[Wayne's World 2]]'' soundtrack. The video consisted of scenes from the movie, with [[Mike Myers (actor)|Mike Myers]] and [[Dana Carvey]], mixed with footage of Jett and her band in a faux concert filmed at [[Irving Plaza]] in [[New York City|NYC]]. At one point during the filming, one person was introduced to the crowd as having been in the original video as he set up to [[Stage diving|stage dive]] for that take. The song was again released as a single by Warner/Reprise with \"Activity Grrrl\" as the B-side.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Joan-Jett-And-The-Blackhearts-I-Love-Rock-Roll/master/717326|title=Joan Jett And The Blackhearts* - I Love Rock & Roll|website=Discogs|language=en|accessdate=2018-12-22}}</ref>\n\n===Popularity===\nJett's version has received many rankings, including:\n* No.&nbsp;85 in [[Q magazine|''Q'' magazine]]'s March 2005 \"100 Greatest Guitar Tracks Ever!\" list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/qlistspage3.htm#Guitar%20Tracks|title=Rocklist.net...Q Magazine Lists..|website=www.rocklistmusic.co.uk|accessdate=2018-12-22}}</ref>\n* No.&nbsp;491 in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'''s \"[[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-151127/|title=500 Greatest Songs of All Time|date=2011-04-07|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|accessdate=2018-12-22}}</ref>\n* No.&nbsp;56 in [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']]'s ''\"''Greatest Songs of All Time\"''.''<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/specials/hot100/charts/top100-titles-60.shtml ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080930202246/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/specials/hot100/charts/top100-titles-60.shtml |date=30 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Chart performance===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1982)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.worldcharts.co.uk/chartfeatures/aus/aus80.htm |title= Australia n\u00b01 Hits - 80's |publisher= Worldcharts.co.uk |accessdate=12 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110520060413/http://www.worldcharts.co.uk/chartfeatures/aus/aus80.htm |archive-date=20 May 2011 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|4|artist=Joan Jett & The Blackhearts|song=I Love Rock'n Roll}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|2|artist=Joan Jett & The Blackhearts|song=I Love Rock'n Roll}}\n|-\n|Canadian [[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'' Top Singles]]<ref>Lwin, Nanda. ''Top 40 Hits: the essential chart guide'' (2000).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infodisc.fr/Bilan_J.php |title=I love rock'n'roll in French Chart |author=Hung Medien |accessdate=12 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130920072658/http://infodisc.fr/Bilan_J.php |archive-date=20 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }} You have to use the index at the top of the page and search \"Joan Jett & the Blackhearts\"</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|6|artist=Joan Jett & The Blackhearts|song=I Love Rock'n Roll|songid=826}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Ireland2|2|artist=Joan Jett and the Blackhearts}}\n|-\n|Italy ([[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana|FIMI]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hitparadeitalia.it/indici/per_interprete/aj.htm |title= Indice per Interprete: J |publisher= HitParadeItalia (it) |accessdate= 12 June 2013}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|42\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|1|artist=Joan Jett & The Blackhearts|song=I Love Rock'n Roll}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|1|artist=Joan Jett & The Blackhearts|song=I Love Rock'n Roll}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|1|artist=Joan Jett & The Blackhearts|song=I Love Rock'n Roll}}\n|-\n|[[South Africa]] ([[Springbok Radio|Springbok]])<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(J).html |title= I love rock'n'roll in South African Chart |author= John Samson |accessdate= 12 June 2013}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|1|artist=Joan Jett & The Blackhearts|song=I Love Rock'n Roll}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Swiss|3|artist=Joan Jett & The Blackhearts|song=I Love Rock'n Roll}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UKsinglesbyname|4|artist=Joan Jett & the Blackhearts}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|1|artist=Joan Jett the Blackhearts}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboarddanceclubplay|31|artist=Joan Jett the Blackhearts}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardmainstreamrock|1|artist=Joan Jett the Blackhearts}}\n|-\n|US [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/80s_files/19820327.html|title=Cash Box Top 100 3/27/82|website=tropicalglen.com|accessdate=27 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150603094214/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/80s_files/19820327.html|archive-date=3 June 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Chart (2015)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Poland|81|year=2015|chartid=1804|accessdate=23 November 2015}}\n|}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1982)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Australia <ref name=\"Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992\">{{cite book|title=Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992<!--|format=doc-->|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|publisher=Australian Chart Book, St Ives, N.S.W |year=1993|isbn=0-646-11917-6|title-link=Kent Music Report}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|Canada <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.6167&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=mhe12pta2k83e08udtq66ot062|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada|work=collectionscanada.gc.ca|accessdate=27 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811145442/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.6167&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=mhe12pta2k83e08udtq66ot062|archive-date=11 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Netherlands <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.top40.nl/bijzondere-lijsten/top-100-jaaroverzichten/1982|title=Top 100-Jaaroverzicht van 1982|first=Stichting Nederlandse Top|last=40|website=Top40.nl}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|25\n|-\n|New Zealand <ref>{{cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/?chart=3871|title=Top Selling Singles of 1982 - The Official New Zealand Music Chart<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|South Africa <ref>{{cite web|title=Top 20 Hit Singles of 1982|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/sahits_1982.html|accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n|UK \n|align=\"center\"|59\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1982.htm|title=Top 100 Hits of 1982/Top 100 Songs of 1982|website=www.musicoutfitters.com}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|U.S. ''Cash Box'' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/80s_files/1982YESP.html|title=Cash Box YE Pop Singles - 1982|website=tropicalglen.com|accessdate=27 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180711062300/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/80s_files/1982YESP.html|archive-date=11 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|}\n\n===All-time charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Chart (1958-2018)\n! Position\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100-60th-anniversary|title=Billboard Hot 100 60th Anniversary Interactive Chart|work=Billboard|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|72\n|}\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Britney Spears version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Love Rock 'n' Roll\n| cover      = Britney Rock n Roll.png\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Britney Spears]]\n| album      = [[Britney (album)|Britney]] and [[Crossroads (Music from the Major Motion Picture)]]\n| released   = {{start date|df=yes|2002|05|27}}<ref name=\"discogs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Britney-Spears-I-Love-Rock-N-Roll/release/1058902|title=Britney Spears \u2013 I Love Rock 'N' Roll|author=|date=n.d.|website=www.discogs.com|publisher=Discogs|accessdate=4 February 2017|quote=Released: 27 May 2002}}</ref>\n| format     = {{flat list|\n*[[Cassette single]]\n*[[CD single]]\n}}\n| recorded   = 2001\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=06}}\n| label      = [[Jive Records|Jive]]\n| writer     = [[Alan Merrill]], [[Jake Hooker (musician)|Jake Hooker]]\n| producer   = [[Rodney Jerkins]]\n| prev_title = [[I'm Not a Girl, Not Yet a Woman]]\n| prev_year  = 2002\n| next_title = [[Anticipating]]\n| next_year  = 2002\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|ITuOddPeYoc|\"I Love Rock 'N' Roll\"}}}}\n}}\n\n===Background, release and composition===\n\"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" was the fourth European single by [[pop music|pop]] singer [[Britney Spears]] from the album ''[[Britney (album)|Britney]]'', released on 27 May 2002. The song was used in her 2002 movie ''[[Crossroads (2002 film)|Crossroads]]'', in which Spears' character Lucy performs it in a karaoke bar. Spears said of the song, \"They asked me to sing karaoke in the movie ''Crossroads'' and I've actually sung I Love Rock 'n' Roll in a lot of clubs that I've been to.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Dingwall|first=John|title=OTR..Off the Record: Your Time Is Up, Jacko; Britney Wants Album Top Slot|newspaper=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|location=Scotland|date=5 November 2001|page=19|url=}}</ref> Spears has publicly stated that the original song is one of her favorites. She listened to the original Arrows Mickie Most-produced version just before she recorded the song, according to [[Jive Records|Jive]] A&R representative Steve Lunt. The scratches performed on this version were performed by Corey Chase at Hit Factory Miami. When promoting the single's release, Spears mistakenly attributed the hit version of the song to [[Pat Benatar]] instead of Joan Jett.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suntimes.com/output/rock/sho-sunday-britney04.html|title=What Britney said, or should have|author=Jim DeRogatis|date=4 November 2001|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011116135611/http://www.suntimes.com/output/rock/sho-sunday-britney04.html|archivedate=16 November 2001|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|accessdate=26 February 2012|author-link=Jim DeRogatis}}</ref>\n\n===Reception===\n\n====Critical====\nSpears' cover was met with mostly favorable reviews. ''[[NME]]''{{'}}s Ted Kessler wrote that Britney \"still works best when making a good pop cheese and dance sandwich: there's the ace [[Rodney Jerkins]]-produced version of [[Joan Jett]]'s 'I Love Rock 'n' Roll', which does exactly what is says on the tin.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Kessler|first=Ted|title=NME Albums Reviews&nbsp;\u2014 Britney Spears : 'Britney Pop's Number One act? She did it again...'|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/britney-spears/5783|accessdate=2 January 2011|newspaper=[[NME]]|date=30 October 2001}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s Barry Walters wrote that \"producer Rodney Jerkins' hip-hop blaspheming of Joan Jett's \"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" doesn't go as far as it should (is a [[Limp Bizkit]] remix in its future?), but it certainly beats what her earlier studio architects did to those [[Sonny and Cher]] (\"[[The Beat Goes On (Sonny & Cher song)|The Beat Goes On]]\" on ''[[...Baby One More Time (album)|...Baby One More Time]]'') and [[Rolling Stones|Stones]] (\"[[(I Can't Get No) Satisfaction]]\" on ''[[Oops!... I Did It Again (album)|Oops!... I Did It Again]]'') songs.\"<ref name=\"RSreview\">{{cite web |author=Barry Walters | title=Britney review |work=Rolling Stone |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/225846/britney |date=22 November 2001 |accessdate=2 January 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070212133054/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/225846/britney |archive-date=12 February 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> Another positive reception came from [[PopMatters]]'s editor Nikki Tranter, who enjoyed that the song is \"different from the average run-of-the-mill pop offering,\" and praised that \"she does strange justice to the tune, vamping up her vocals and turning out something, that while silly and camp, is actually a fun listen.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Tranter|first=Nikki|title=Britney Spears: Britney <PopMatters>|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/spearsbritney-britney|accessdate=2 January 2012|newspaper=[[PopMatters]]|date=5 November 2001}}</ref> In contrast, David Browne wrote for ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' that \"her remake is neither imaginative (it simply xeroxes Joan Jett's arrangement) nor all that believable.\"<ref>[http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,183907~4~~britney,00.html Britney | Music]. EW.com (12 November 2001). Retrieved 2 January 2012.</ref>\n\n====Commercial====\n\"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" charted moderately upon release, reaching the top twenty in most regions. The song was moderately successful in the UK, where it peaked at #13 (which, at the time, was Spears' lowest peak for a single released there, until \"[[Radar (song)|Radar]]\" only managed to reach #46 in 2009, and then \"[[I Wanna Go]]\", which peaked at #111). The single sold a total of 65,000 copies.<ref>[http://www.ukbritney.tv/discography/3britney_05ilrnr.php Britney Spears&nbsp;\u2014 I Love Rock 'n' Roll (UK)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070509143315/http://www.ukbritney.tv/discography/3britney_05ilrnr.php |date=9 May 2007 }} ''UKBritney.tv''  Retrieved 22 May 2007</ref> It was also certified Gold in Australia.\n\n===Promotion===\nDirected by Chris Applebaum, the music video for \"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" shows Spears with her own band, a stack of speakers and flashing lights. The video begins in [[black and white]] and switches to and from color throughout. It was shot at The Inn, a bar in Long Beach, New York. The video was ranked at #2 on the 100 Best Videos of 2002 list during [[MTV Latin America]]'s countdown. A \"Director's Cut\" version of the video was later leaked, containing previously unseen scenes.\n\nThe song was performed live during Spears' [[Dream Within a Dream Tour]] (2001\u201302). In 2016, it was added to the revamped set list of her [[Las Vegas]] residency show, [[Britney: Piece of Me]] (2016\u201317), marking the first time Spears performed the song in 14 years. During the performance, Britney Spears rode a mechanical electric guitar, which simulated a mechanical bull, as it rotated on stage. The same prop electric guitar had been used during her [[Femme Fatale Tour]] (2011) for a segment in which she covered the song \"[[Burning Up (Madonna song)|Burning Up]]\" by [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]. At the [[2016 Billboard Music Awards]], the song was performed as part of a medley.\n\n===Track listings===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*;European 2 tracks CD single\n# \"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" (Album Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:06\n# \"[[Overprotected]]\" ([[Rodney Jerkins|Darkchild]] Remix)&nbsp;\u2014 3:18\n\n*;European/Australian CD single\n# \"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" (Album Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:08\n# \"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" (Karaoke Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:06\n# \"Overprotected\" (Darkchild Remix)&nbsp;\u2014 3:20\n# \"[[I'm Not a Girl, Not Yet a Woman]]\" (Metro Remix)&nbsp;\u2014 5:26\n\n*;German 2 tracks CD single\n# \"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" (Album Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:07\n# \"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" (Karaoke Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:05\n\n*;German CD single\n# \"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" (Album Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:07\n# \"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" (Karaoke Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:05\n# \"Overprotected\" (Riprock 'N Alex G Remix)&nbsp;\u2014 3:25\n# \"I'm Not a Girl, Not Yet a Woman\" (Metro Remix)&nbsp;\u2014 5:24\n\n{{col-2}}\n*;Japanese CD maxi single\n# \"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" (Album Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:06\n# \"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" (Karaoke Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:04\n# \"Overprotected\" (Darkchild Remix)&nbsp;\u2014 3:20\n# \"I'm Not a Girl, Not Yet a Woman\" (Metro Remix)&nbsp;\u2014 5:25\n# \"[[I'm a Slave 4 U]]\" ([[Thunderpuss]] Radio Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 3:18