y announced his bid for the Official Christmas Number one. As with their last release \"[[We Built This City#LadBaby version|We Built This City]]\", all proceeds from the single went to [[The Trussell Trust]]. He said, \"We were blown away by the support we received on our Christmas Number 1 single last year and how far that money has gone into changing the lives of families living in poverty across the UK. We're continually looking for ways we can support food bank charity the Trussell Trust further as the size of the problem still facing so many adults (and children) is huge and we ALL need to do whatever we can to say goodbye to poverty once and for all in the UK! If we can use our social media presence for good by singing about sausage rolls, giving people something to smile about and helping families eat this year, then why wouldn\u2019t we. Officially, the most unanticipated single of the decade...AGAIN!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ladbaby-announces-bid-for-2019-christmas-number-1-with-new-single-i-love-sausage-rolls__27944/|title=LadBaby announces 2019 bid for Christmas Number 1|website=officialcharts.com|date=December 9, 2019|accessdate=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Charts===\nOn December 20, 2019, the song song entered the [[UK Singles Chart]] at number one, claiming the [[List of UK Singles Chart Christmas number ones|Christmas number one]] with 93,000 chart sales and with 85,000 of that total coming via downloads. It was also the fastest-selling download since Artists for Grenfell version of \"[[Bridge over Troubled Water (song)|Bridge over Troubled Water]]\" in June 2017. LadBaby became the third act to have two consecutive Christmas number one singles and the first to have two successive novelty Christmas number ones in the UK. After reaching number one, LadBaby said, \"How have we done this again? It\u2019s the best feeling in the world - it's a Christmas miracle yet again! Thank you everybody for supporting us once again, and all for an amazing cause. It's going to the Trussell Trust \u2013 to the 14 million people living in poverty in the UK. Who doesn\u2019t love a sausage roll at Christmas?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ladbaby-score-second-official-christmas-number-1-with-i-love-sausage-rolls-its-a-christmas-miracle-again-__28042/|title=On a roll! LadBaby score second Official Christmas Number 1|website=officialcharts.com|date=December 20, 2019|accessdate=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Chart (2019)\n! Peak<br/>position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2019/12/aria-chart-watch-556/|title=ARIA Chart Watch #556|publisher=auspOp|date=December 21, 2019|accessdate=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n| 100\n|-\n{{single chart|Ireland3|59|artist=LadBaby|rowheader=true|accessdate=January 4, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| New Zealand Hot Singles ([[Recorded Music NZ|RMNZ]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/hotsingles?chart=4794|title=NZ Hot Singles Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=December 23, 2019|accessdate=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n| 20\n|-\n{{single chart|Scotland|1|date=20191220|rowheader=true|refname=scb|accessdate=January 4, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UK|1|date=20191220|rowheader=true|accessdate=January 4, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Hot Rock Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/rock-songs/2019-12-28|title=Top Rock Songs Chart {{!}} December 28, 2019|work=Billboard|accessdate=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n| 10\n|}\n\n==Other cover versions==\n\"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" has been covered and sampled by artists such as:\n*[[Tiny Tim (musician)|Tiny Tim]], on his 1980 album ''Chameleon''.\n* [[L'Arc~En~Ciel]], as an international single in 2011 and it in a Pepsi commercial in Japan.\n* [[Lee Da-hae]], as a 2007 single with versions in both English and Korean.\n*[[Five (band)|Five]], who sampled the song in \"[[Everybody Get Up]]\".\n* [[Joseph Simmons|Reverend Run]], who sampled the song in \"Mind on the Road\" from his solo album ''[[Distortion (Joseph Simmons album)|Distortion]]''.\n* [[\"Weird Al\" Yankovic]], who parodied the song as \"[[I Love Rocky Road]]\".\n* Forever Young, who reached #27 in France in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.co/song/3588 |title=I Love Rock'n'roll by Forever Young - Music Charts |website=Acharts.co |date= |accessdate=2016-10-10}}</ref>\n* Fast Forward Highway, for the video game ''[[Just Dance 2017]]''.\n*[[Eminem]], who sampled the instrumental in \"Remind Me\" from his ninth studio album ''[[Revival (Eminem album)|Revival]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whosampled.com/Eminem/Remind-Me/|title=Remind Me by Eminem - Samples, Covers and Remixes|work=[[WhoSampled]]|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref>\n* Lipsaset, who released a 2014 version in Finnish called \"Aina rock'n'roll\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.magnumlive.fi/lipsaset-julkaisee-70-luvun-i-love-rock-n-roll-hitin-suomeksi/|title=Lipsaset julkaisee 70-luvun I Love Rock'n'Roll -hitin suomeksi - MagnumLive|website=www.magnumlive.fi}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles of 1982|List of ''Billboard'' Hot 100 number-one singles of 1982]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.iloverocknroll.org History of the song \"I Love Rock 'n Roll\"]\n* [http://alanmerrill.tumblr.com/post/39427829851/the-arrows-enduring-legacy-from-bill-harrys-rock-n Bill Harry's Merseybeat article]\n* {{MetroLyrics song|britney-spears|i-love-rock-n-roll}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Joan Jett}}\n{{Britney Spears singles}}\n{{Alex Gaudino}}\n{{UK Christmas number ones in the 2010s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:I Love Rock N Roll}}\n[[Category:1975 songs]]\n[[Category:1975 singles]]\n[[Category:1982 singles]]\n[[Category:2002 singles]]\n[[Category:Arrows (British band) songs]]\n[[Category:Jive Records singles]]\n[[Category:RAK Records singles]]\n[[Category:Joan Jett songs]]\n[[Category:Britney Spears songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Dutch Top 40 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Single Top 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:RPM Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Chris Applebaum]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Mickie Most]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Rodney Jerkins]]\n[[Category:Songs about music]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Australia]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Christmas number-one singles in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Black-and-white music videos]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Short description|1975 rock single}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Love Rock 'n' Roll\n| cover      = Arrows I Love Rock n Roll.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = 2004 re-issue\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Arrows (British band)|Arrows]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = [[Broken Down Heart]]\n| released   = July 1975\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 1975\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hard rock]]\n| length     = 2:48\n| label      = [[RAK Records|RAK]]\n| writer     = [[Alan Merrill]], [[Jake Hooker (musician)|Jake Hooker]]\n| producer   = [[Mickie Most]]\n| prev_title = Hard Hearted\n| prev_year  = 1975\n| next_title = Once Upon a Time\n| next_year  = 1976\n}}\n\n\"'''I Love Rock 'n' Roll'''\" is a [[Rock music|rock]] song written by [[Alan Merrill]] and [[Jake Hooker (musician)|Jake Hooker]] and first recorded by the [[Arrows (British band)|Arrows]] in 1975. It is best known for its 1982 cover version by [[Joan Jett|Joan Jett & the Blackhearts]], which was released as the first single from her [[I Love Rock 'n Roll (album)|album of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Cad|first=Saint|title=10 More Famous Songs With Unknown Originals|url=http://listverse.com/2012/10/14/10-more-famous-songs-with-unknown-originals/|work=listverse.com|accessdate=21 June 2013}}</ref> Jett's rendition became her highest-charting hit, reaching number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100]] and becoming the [[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1982|No. 3 song for 1982]]. The single was certified platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]], representing two million units shipped to stores. Jett's version was inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/press-release/the-recording-academy-announces-2016-grammy-hall-of-fame-inductees|title=The Recording Academy Announces 2016 Grammy Hall of Fame Inductees|work=Recording Academy|accessdate=February 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Arrows original version==\nThe song was originally recorded and [[release (music)|released]] by [[Arrows (British band)|Arrows]] in 1975 on [[Rak Records]], with Merrill on lead vocals and guitar and [[Mickie Most]] producing. Merrill wrote the music and lyrics. In an interview with Songfacts, Merrill said he wrote the song as \"a knee-jerk response to [[the Rolling Stones]]' '[[It's Only Rock 'n Roll (But I Like It)]]'.\"<ref name=\"Outsight Radio Hours interview\">{{cite web|title=Outsight Radio Hours interview, 12 February 2012|url=https://archive.org/details/AlanMerrillOnOutsightRadioHours|accessdate=18 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"songfacts\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=2422 \n |title=I Love Rock and Roll \n |work=Songfacts.com \n |accessdate=2009-09-20 \n |url-status=dead \n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226214725/http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=2422 \n |archive-date=26 February 2017 \n |df= \n}}</ref>\nThis version was first released as a [[B-side]], but was soon re-recorded and flipped to [[A-side]] status on a subsequent pressing of the record. Arrows performed the song in 1975 on the [[Muriel Young]]-produced show ''45'', after which Young offered Arrows a weekly UK television series, ''[[Arrows (TV series)|Arrows]]'', which was broadcast on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] starting in March 1976.<ref name=\"Cover song\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-29568083 \"Ten hits you may not know were cover versions\"]. BBC News. Retrieved 14 October 2014</ref>\n\n==Joan Jett version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Love Rock 'n Roll\n| cover      = File:I Love Rock n Roll by Joan Jett and the Blackheads US vinyl single.png\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Artwork for US and Australian edition\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Joan Jett|Joan Jett and the Blackhearts]]\n| album      = [[I Love Rock 'n Roll (album)|I Love Rock 'n Roll]]\n| B-side     = \"You Don't Know What You've Got\" or \"Love is Pain\"\n| released   = January 19, 1982\n| format     = [[7-inch single]], [[12-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 1981\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hard rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.allmusic.com/song/i-love-rock-n-roll-mt0010368331 |first= Steve |last= Huey |title= I Love Rock N' Roll \u2013 Song Review |work= [[AllMusic|Allmusic]] |publisher= [[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate= February 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title= Rock Obituaries - Knocking On Heaven's Door |first= Nick |last= Talevski\n|publisher= [[Music Sales Group|Omnibus Press]] |quote= Cordell joined [[Kenny Laguna]], his former session player and then manager of Joan Jett & the Blackhearts, to co-produce the group's chart-topping hard-rock anthem 'I Love Rock 'N Roll'. |year= 2006 |page= 100 |isbn= 978-1-8460-9091-2}}</ref>\n| length     = 2:55 (LP version)<br>2:45 (U.S. single edit)\n| label      = [[Boardwalk Records|Boardwalk]]\n| writer     = [[Alan Merrill]], [[Jake Hooker (musician)|Jake Hooker]]\n| producer   = [[Ritchie Cordell]], [[Kenny Laguna]]\n| prev_title = [[Bad Reputation (Joan Jett song)|Bad Reputation]]\n| prev_year  = 1981\n| next_title = [[Crimson and Clover#Joan Jett version|Crimson and Clover]]\n| next_year  = 1982\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|t5ecqUhec-s|\"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" (''TopPop'', 1982)}}}}\n}}\n{{listen\n|filename=I Love Rock N Roll sample.ogg\n|title=\"I Love Rock N Roll\"\n|description=[[Joan Jett|Joan Jett and the Blackhearts]]' \"I Love Rock N Roll\" from ''[[I Love Rock 'n Roll (album)|I Love Rock 'n Roll]]''\n|filetype=[[Ogg]]}}\n\n[[Joan Jett]] saw the [[Arrows (British band)|Arrows]] perform \"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" on their weekly UK television series ''[[Arrows (TV series)|Arrows]]''<ref name=\"Outsight Radio Hours interview\"/> while she was touring England with [[the Runaways]] in 1976.<ref name=\"Cover song\"/> She first recorded the song in 1979 with two of the [[Sex Pistols]], [[Steve Jones (musician)|Steve Jones]] and [[Paul Cook]]. This first version was released on vinyl in 1979 on Vertigo records as a B-side to \"[[You Don't Own Me]]\". In 1981, Jett re-recorded the song, this time with her band, [[the Blackhearts]]. This recording became a U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] number-one single for seven weeks.<ref>[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]] (2004). ''The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits'', 8th Edition (Billboard Publications), page 322.</ref>\n\n===Music video===\nThe black-and-white [[music video]] for \"I Love Rock 'n' Roll\" received heavy play by the fledgling [[MTV]] network. It featured Jett and the Blackhearts traveling to a small, dingy bar and then exciting the drunken crowd by performing the song and yelling out its [[refrain|chorus]]. A snippet of Jett's 1981 hit \"[[Bad Reputation (Joan Jett song)|Bad Reputation]]\" can be heard at the beginning of the video. The video was originally in color, but it was converted to black and white because Jett hated the look of her red leather jumpsuit in color.<ref>{{Citation|title=Joan Jett & the Blackhearts: I Love Rock 'n' Roll (Video 1982)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6973600/trivia|accessdate=2018-12-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993 Joan Jett & the Blackhearts made another music video for the song as part of the ''[[Wayne's World 2]]'' soundtrack. The video consisted of scenes from the movie, with [[Mike Myers (actor)|Mike Myers]] and [[Dana Carvey]], mixed with footage of Jett and her band in a faux concert filmed at [[Irving Plaza]] in [[New York City|NYC]]. At one point during the filming, one person was introduced to the crowd as having been in the original video as he set up to [[Stage diving|stage dive]] for that take. The song was again released as a single by Warner/Reprise with \"Activity Grrrl\" as the B-side.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Joan-Jett-And-The-Blackhearts-I-Love-Rock-Roll/master/717326|title=Joan Jett And The Blackhearts* - I Love Rock & Roll|website=Discogs|language=en|accessdate=2018-12-22}}</ref>\n\n===Popularity===\nJett's version has received many rankings, including:\n* No.&nbsp;85 in [[Q magazine|''Q'' magazine]]'s March 2005 \"100 Greatest Guitar Tracks Ever!\" list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/qlistspage3.htm#Guitar%20Tracks|title=Rocklist.net...Q Magazine Lists..|website=www.rocklistmusic.co.uk|accessdate=2018-12-22}}</ref>\n* No.&nbsp;491 in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'''s \"[[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-151127/|title=500 Greatest Songs of All Time|date=2011-04-07|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|accessdate=2018-12-22}}</ref>\n* No.&nbsp;56 in [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']]'s ''\"''Greatest Songs of All Time\"''.''<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/specials/hot100/charts/top100-titles-60.shtml ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080930202246/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/specials/hot100/charts/top100-titles-60.shtml |date=30 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Chart performance===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1982)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.worldcharts.co.uk/chartfeatures/aus/aus80.htm |title= Australia n\u00b01 Hits - 80's |publisher= Worldcharts.co.uk |accessdate=12 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110520060413/http://www.worldcharts.co.uk/chartfeatures/aus/aus80.htm |archive-date=20 May 2011 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|4|artist=Joan Jett & The Blackhearts|song=I Love Rock'n Roll}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|2|artist=Joan Jett & The Blackhearts|song=I Love Rock'n Roll}}\n|-\n|Canadian [[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'' Top Singles]]<ref>Lwin, Nanda. ''Top 40 Hits: the essential chart guide'' (2000).</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infodisc.fr/Bilan_J.php |title=I love rock'n'roll in French Chart |author=Hung Medien |accessdate=12 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130920072658/http://infodisc.fr/Bilan_J.php |archive-date=20 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }} You have to use the index at the top of the page and search \"Joan Jett & the Blackhearts\"</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|6|artist=Joan Jett & The Blackhearts|song=I Love Rock'n Roll|songid=826}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Ireland2|2|artist=Joan Jett and the Blackhearts}}\n|-\n|Italy ([[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana|FIMI]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hitparadeitalia.it/indici/per_interprete/aj.htm |title= Indice per Interprete: J |publisher= HitParadeItalia (it) |accessdate= 12 June 2013}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|42\n|-\